L3 LIVE 2-MONITOR HDMI VERIFY — PASS
=====================================
date:                 2026-07-19 20:33 EDT
verified_at_commit:   2a20f8b
certifies_version:    0.2.0
hardware:             Dell laptop, eDP-1 (1920x1200, primary) + HDMI-1 (1600x900, right-of)
wm:                   dwm 6.5 + dwm-ipc patch, live /tmp/dwm.sock
operator:             kleinpanic (physical unplug/replug of HDMI cable)
daemon:               xrandrw --watch, WINDOW_MANAGEMENT=1, LOG_LEVEL=debug

VERIFIED (full true chain, real hardware, no mocks):
  physical unplug -> RandR event -> watch_loop -> apply_once -> on_settled
    -> recorded displaced x3 (output=HDMI-1)
  physical replug -> apply_once -> on_settled
    -> restored displaced x3 (output=HDMI-1), dropped=3 skipped=0
  focus: relocate_focus_restored xid=35651589 (the operator's pre-unplug window)

RESULT: all 3 windows returned to HDMI-1; exactly ONE displace cycle and ONE
restore cycle (no bounce-induced double movement); operator focus preserved.
Operator verdict: "it works perfectly".

SCOPE OF THIS EVIDENCE — READ BEFORE RELYING ON IT
--------------------------------------------------
ONE machine, ONE topology, ONE operator, ONE session. This is a single manual
run on the hardware named above. It is not a matrix, not repeated, and not
independently reproducible by a third party. It says the chain CAN work on that
configuration; it does not establish that it works on other hardware, on docks,
on 3+ heads, or on mirrored outputs (which the matcher declines to map at all).

EVIDENCE FILES ARE NOT INDEPENDENTLY VERIFIABLE. The logs cited below live under
.planning/, which is GITIGNORED and therefore absent from the repository, from
the sdist, and from every clone. Nobody but the operator can inspect them. This
stamp is an OPERATOR ATTESTATION, not auditable provenance, and should be read
with exactly that weight:
  .planning/debug/evidence/livetest-UX-PASS-2026-07-19-2033.log   (this run)
  .planning/debug/evidence/livetest-PASS-2026-07-19-1929.log      (P1 functional pass)
  .planning/debug/evidence/newdaemon2.log                          (the original 04:21 failure)

HISTORY: two earlier live attempts FAILED (2026-07-19 ~04:21) with windows
stranded on eDP-1. Root cause was three necessary+jointly-sufficient links:
matcher connected-preferring tie-break, scrub_stale moved onto read #2, and
CRTC-liveness edge detection. See .planning/debug/resolved/relocate-replug-bounce.md

DRIFT POLICY (enforced by ci/check_l3_stamp.sh at release time)
---------------------------------------------------------------
This stamp goes STALE. The release gate FAILS if src/xrandrw/ changed between
verified_at_commit and the released tag, and WARNS for any other drift. It also
fails if certifies_version does not match the tag, so a stamp never silently
carries forward into a later release. To release code with src/ changes, either
re-run the live verify and update this file, or record a reviewed waiver in the
"drift_waived_through" field below, with a written reason.
(Fields are parsed only at column 0; indented mentions like this one are prose.)

To record a waiver, add a line at column 0:
    drift_waived_through: <sha>
followed by a written waiver_reason. The waiver is pinned to that sha and expires
the moment any later commit touches src/xrandrw/.

CURRENT STATUS: STALE — NO WAIVER RECORDED, RELEASE INTENTIONALLY BLOCKED
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
This stamp does NOT cover current HEAD, and no waiver is recorded, so
ci/check_l3_stamp.sh will FAIL the release. That is deliberate and correct.

Some drift since 2a20f8b is provably irrelevant to this evidence:
  - 8029c7b refactor(watch): pure code motion. The churn-debounce arithmetic moved
    verbatim out of _apply_if_changed into _debounce_ms_for_churn; no constant,
    comparison, or branch changed. _bounce_settled -- the hold-down function this
    run actually exercised -- is BYTE-IDENTICAL (verified by diffing the body).
  - f585670, 7c5065c fix(wallpaper): confined to the wallpaper backend.
  - 1ae719b docs: argparse help-string text in cli.py only; no behaviour.

But the disqualifying drift is in relocate.py, which is squarely ON the certified
unplug -> displace -> replug -> restore path:
  - dfbd06c fix(relocate): a REJECTED restore no longer logs success and drops
    the record.
  - b132b90 fix(relocate): an UNCONFIRMED focus now aborts the verbs instead of
    mangling windows.
These change what the restore path DOES on the exact failure modes this live run
was meant to exercise. Waiving them as "unrelated" would be false, and would
reproduce in prose the very rubber-stamp this gate was written to eliminate.

REQUIRED BEFORE v0.2.0 SHIPS: re-run the live 2-monitor unplug/replug verify on
